observations.recommendation:
We recommended that management:

Exhaust and avail of all remedies to enforce the remittance of the collections due for the government;

Direct the Collecting Officers to restitute the whole amount of unremitted collections;

Thoroughly trace the reported vague accounts from "Municipal Employees"; and

Adopt proper procedures and controls pertaining to collections and remittances and to strictly monitor the personnel performing such functions.

We recommended for the Municipal Mayor to:

Direct the HRMO to create an employee manual that will define the job description, rights, and responsibilities, among others, of all the employees within the Municipality;

Issue a uniform and clear-cut policy on the hiring of Job Order workers to strengthen internal controls pertaining thereto;

Reduce/limit the hiring of job order workers and fill-up vacant positions; and

Evaluate and determine the appropriate personnel complement of each office.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to:
Direct he GSO and the MAO to establish an effective and practical system that would ensure the swift and regular reconciliation of records of both offices pertaining to the Municipality’s Property, Plant and Equipment;
Conduct a complete physical count of all properties;
Implement a system of property management such as using property tags and assigning property numbers for each of the property owned to facilitate easy identification; and
Direct the GSO to correctly provides all the necessary data required in the RPCPPE for proper identification of all PPE items.

We recommended to the Management to:
Enforce the immediate liquidation and/or settlement of all outstanding cash advances;
Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to officials/employees who have previous unliquidated cash advances as well as granting multiple cash advances to the same employees regardless of the purpose;
Trace the identity of personnel from the vague accounts - “Municipal Employees” and “Municipal Employees and Officers”, and enforce the immediate liquidation of the same;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to expedite the request for the write-off of long outstanding cash advances that are considered dormant in accordance with the guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; and
Strictly adhere to the guidelines set forth in COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997, in the granting and liquidation of cash advances.

We recommend that management:

Ensure that balances presented in the trial balance accurately reflect the balances in its subsidiary ledger and other supporting schedules;

Regularly reconcile the cashbook balances with the subsidiary ledgers to ensure accuracy of the cash accounts;

Exert efforts to account all unrecorded debit/credit memos and other unrecorded reconciling items, retrieve the previous accounting records as well as coordinate with the bank for possible re-printing of the memos to eventually account/record the total amount of the reconciling items; and

Prepare and effect the necessary adjusting entries for the reconciling items found in the bank reconciliation statements that require adjustment in the books.

We recommended that management:

Adequately plan and thoroughly study each project before proposing it to be included as one of the projects to be funded by the 20% LGDF;

Enforce stringent control procedures in the disbursement of the fund to ensure that it is utilized only for its intended purpose/s to preclude the issuance of audit suspensions/disallowances;

Strictly adhere to the pertinent provisions of law, rules, and regulations relative to the utilization of the 20% Development Fund, so that constituents could directly enjoy the benefits for which the fund was primarily established; and

Submit an explanation on the recurrence of such deficiency for us to decide whether to suspend/disallow said transactions in the audit.

We recommended that management prioritize the: 

1) creation of the Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Office (MENRO) to focus on the issues and concerns on solid waste management; and

2) procurement of additional dump truck and backhoe for the operation and maintenance of the Sanitary Landfill (SLF);

